          <h3>Today, much of Earth’s natural beauty has been marred by human activities. Once clear rivers are now
            polluted, choked with industrial waste and plastic, while deforestation has stripped away vast expanses of
            forests that once served as the lungs of the planet. The air is thick with pollution in many regions,
            leading to smog-filled skies that obscure the stars and make breathing hazardous in some cities. The oceans,
            once teeming with life, are now plagued by overfishing, coral bleaching, and plastic islands floating in the
            currents</h3>
          <h3>The polar ice caps are melting at an alarming rate due to climate change, raising sea levels and
            threatening coastal communities. Industrialization, urban sprawl, and relentless resource extraction have
            left scars on the landscape, while the atmosphere has become overloaded with carbon emissions, trapping heat
            and disrupting weather patterns. The delicate balance of Earth’s ecosystems has been thrown into disarray,
            and the consequences of this imbalance are becoming more evident with each passing year.</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="col-sm-6">
          <img src="images/ugly2.png" alt="" width="650px">
        </div>

      </div><br><br>
      <div class="row">
        <div class="col-sm-6">
          <img src="images/ugly3.png" alt="" width="700px">
        </div>
        <div class="col-sm-6">
          <h3>In the past, Earth was a masterpiece of natural beauty, shaped over millions of years by geological
            forces, evolution, and the delicate balance of its ecosystems. Lush rainforests, such as the Amazon and the
            Congo, were expansive and teemed with diverse species, many of which remain undiscovered to this day. These
            forests acted as the planet's lungs, absorbing carbon dioxide and releasing oxygen, maintaining a climate
            that supported a vast array of life. Mountain ranges, carved by the slow movement of tectonic plates, stood
            tall and untouched, their snow-capped peaks shimmering under the sun, while sprawling savannas and
            grasslands hosted herds of wildlife that roamed freely across the plains.</h3>
          <h3>The oceans, covering over 70% of the Earth's surface, were once thriving nurseries of marine life, home to
            coral reefs so vibrant they were known as the rainforests of the sea. Coastal areas, free from human
            development, were pristine, with mangroves and wetlands serving as natural buffers against storms and
            providing breeding grounds for countless species. Rivers flowed freely, unencumbered by dams or pollution,
            carving valleys and shaping landscapes in their natural course. Glaciers in the polar regions and on
            mountaintops were vast and stable, reflecting sunlight and regulating global temperatures through the
            ice-albedo effect.
          </h3>
